attributes.magic: PE32 executable (GUI) Intel 80386, for MS Windows

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Cobalt Strike's resources/reverse.bin signature for versions 2.5 to 4.x
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: gssincla@google.com

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Identifies Metasploit 64 bit reverse tcp shellcode.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Elastic Security

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a malicious network stager, likely a variant of a Metasploit or Cobalt Strike loader. It utilizes shellcode-like techniques for evasion and payload delivery, including: 1) Custom API resolution via PEB (Process Environment Block) traversal and ROR13 hashing to bypass static analysis of imports; 2) Loading 'ws2_32.dll' to establish a network connection; 3) Dynamic allocation of executable memory using VirtualAlloc (hash 0xe553a458); 4) Downloading an encrypted or raw payload over a socket (using connect/recv) and jumping to its entry point. The presence of an RWX section (.tqxu) containing the entry point further confirms its role as a self-extracting or staged loader.
